$values.value: What happens when you leave care depends on:
how your local council does things
This guide is for you if your status is:
Leaving care can feel like a challenging time, but your council's leaving care team must support and prepare you.
start getting ready to leave care at
helps to prepare you for leaving care and keeps supporting you afterwards. They must explain what support you have the right to and help you get access to it.
You’ll normally meet your PA when you’re 16 or 17. Your social worker must introduce you to them before you leave care.
They must meet with you at least once every 8 weeks to work on your Pathway Plan.
You’ll have a 'needs assessment' to find out what help and services you’ll need when you leave care.
This will included as part of your Pathway Plan.
your plans and goals for when you leave care
Your council must review it with you at least once every 6 months. You or your personal adviser can also ask for a review at any time.
Before you leave care, you'll have a ‘statutory review meeting’ to chat about your future. You’ll talk about things like:
if you want to stay in education or training, or find a job
Who will be at the meeting?
an independent reviewing officer (they check things are done properly)
professionals, like a teacher or doctor
an advocate (someone to explain your rights and speak up for you), if you ask for one
any other people that support you
They can explain your rights to you and make sure your voice is heard. If you want, they can help you
Your PA must continue to support you until you're 21. They must meet with you at least once every 8 weeks.
If you tell your council you want to keep your PA after 21, until your 25th birthday, they must give you this support.

$values.title: Care terms explained
$values.text: What care terms mean and how this affects what support you might get

$values.value: Learn what the terms ‘in care’, ‘looked after’, and ‘care leaver’ mean.
If you’re a care leaver, it means you:
were in a care setting (like a foster home or children’s home) or looked after
are getting ready to live independently
This is a big change, but there's help to do this. (need link for this)
You are not ‘looked after’ if you:
live with a parent or someone with parental responsibility for more than 6 months after the age of 16 (this includes someone that a court has ordered you to live with)
are under a Special Guardianship Order
What is a Special Guardianship Order?

This is where a judge has given someone other than your birth parents ‘parental responsibility’. This person is called a ‘special guardian’. Your special guardian has legal responsibility to care for you.

$values.description: What is a care leaver status?

$values.value: What is a care leaver status?
Depending on the time you were looked after for, you may have a ‘care leaver status’. Having a status gives you the right to get certain support.
